We compute the first few derivatives of $f(x) = x \ln(x)$ and look for a
pattern.

\begin{align*}
\begin{array}{ccl}
f'(x) &&= \ln(x) + 1 \\
f''(x) &&= 1/x \\
f'''(x) &&= -1/x^2 \\
f^{(4)}(x) &&= 2/x^3 \\
f^{(5)}(x) &&= -6/x^3 \\
\end{array}
\end{align*}

After the second derivative, we notice that the derivative is a
fraction, with a constant in the numerator and a power of \emph{x} in
the denominator. In fact, we can write this pattern as

\begin{align*}
f^{(n)}(x) = \frac{(n-2)! (-1)^n}{x^{n-1}}
\end{align*}

for all \emph{n} $\geq$ 2.

The only derivative that is different is the first one. Thus, our
piecewise function describing the derivative is:

: f\^{}\{(n)\}(x) = \textbackslash{}begin\{cases\} \textbackslash{}ln(x)
\& n = 1 \textbackslash{}\textbackslash{} \textbackslash{}frac\{ (n-2)!
(-1)\^{}n \}\{x\^{}\{n-1\}\} \& n \textgreater{} 1
\textbackslash{}end\{cases\}

